	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>New strategy for African rice sector development launched </h1>

			
			<h4>
												18 March 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>In February 2012 the Africa Rice Centre launched its new 10-year strategic plan to support attainment of 90% self-sufficiency in rice in Africa by 2020. Currently Africa imports around 40% of its rice needs, ‘which makes it highly exposed to international market shocks’. It is hoped that ‘productivity enhancing research and development activities’ will increase production from 18.4 million tonnes in 2010 to 46.8 million tonnes by 2020. In addition, ‘future ready’ rice-based production systems are to be developed to assist farmers in dealing with climate change.</p><p>In Nigeria, with high levels of rice imports, rice farmers have appealed to the federal government for increased support, including through the increased provision of working capital to allow more land to be planted under rice and to promote mechanisation of the sector.&nbsp; If such support could be extended, it is argued, then existing farmers could extend the area under rice by 500–700%. In the face of climate change assistance is also being sought for irrigation projects in rice farming areas.&nbsp;</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p><i>Thecropsite.com</i>, ‘research strategy to realise Africa’s rice potential unveiled’, 3 February 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.thecropsite.com/news/10212/research-strategy-to-realise-africas-rice-potential-unveiled" target="_self">http://www.thecropsite.com/news/10212/research-strategy-to-realise-afric...</a></p><p><i>Leadership</i> (Abuja), ‘Rice farmers under pressure to meet rising demand’, 9 February 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://allafrica.com/stories/201202090586.html" target="_self">http://allafrica.com/stories/201202090586.html</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Enhanced research and development is just one part of the challenge faced in the African rice sector. As recent appeals from Nigerian rice farmers illustrate, systemic issues linked to the access of smallholder farmers to investment and working capital also need to be addressed. What does not appear to be a significant constraint is a local market for rice, given the rapidly growing expansion of rice consumption across a range of African countries, although there remains work to do in order to deliver rice to major urban centres of a quality and packaging acceptable to local consumers in some areas.</p><p>If the expanding African demand is to be met by expanding African production, regional collaboration in establishing common standards for rice could play an important role. In addition, there would appear to be a need to reconcile the use of national trade policy measures in the rice sector (export bans and import restrictions in particular) with the development of regional rice supply chains and regional trade liberalisation commitments.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
